= Origin and Early Evolution of Amniotes

== Origin of Amniotes

#slide[
  - *Amniotes* (羊膜动物) are a monophyletic group that arose from *anthracosaurs* (炭黑龙类) in the early Carboniferous period.
  - *Diadectes* (阔齿龙) is the likely sister taxon of amniotes.
  - Early amniotes were small and lizardlike, radiating by the early Permian.
]

== Evolution of Amniotes

#slide[
  - The evolutionary origin of amniotes occurred by evolution of an *amniotic egg* (羊膜卵).
  - This made reproduction on land possible.
  - The amniote assemblage includes nonavian reptiles, birds, and mammals.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-1").path),
  )
]

== Skull Fenestration Patterns

#slide[
  - *Anapsid* (无孔类): No temporal openings behind the orbit (ancestral condition, turtles).
  - *Diapsid* (双孔类): Two temporal openings (one pair low on cheeks, one pair dorsal).
  - *Synapsid* (合弓类): Single pair of temporal openings low on cheeks (mammals and their ancestors).
]

== Cladogram of Living Amniota

#slide[
  - Cladogram shows monophyletic groups of living Amniota.
  - Skulls represent the ancestral condition of the three groups (Anapsid, Diapsid, Synapsid).
  - Modern skulls are often modified by loss or fusion of bones.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-2").path),
  )
]

== Derived Characters of Amniotes: The Amniotic Egg

#slide[
  - *Amnion* (羊膜): Encloses embryo in fluid (cushioning, aqueous medium).
  - *Allantois* (尿囊): Stores metabolic wastes; respiratory surface.
  - *Chorion* (绒毛膜): Surrounds contents; highly vascularized for respiration.
  - *Yolk sac* (卵黄囊): Nutrient storage.
  - *Shell* (卵壳): Mineralized/flexible; mechanical support; semipermeable barrier.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-3").path),
  )
]

== Other Derived Characters

#slide[
  - *Rib Ventilation* (肋式呼吸): *Aspiration* (抽气) by expanding thoracic cavity using costal muscles (negative pressure breathing).
  - *Thicker, Waterproof Skin*: *Keratinized* (角质化) (beta keratin in reptiles), lipid-rich to limit water loss; not used for respiration.
]

= Characteristics of Nonavian Reptiles

== Distinctions from Amphibians

#slide[
  - *Skin*: Tough, dry, scaly skin protects against desiccation (干燥) and physical injury.
  - Scales are keratinized (beta keratin) and derived from epidermis.
  - Skin is not used for respiration.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-4").path),
  )
]

== Physiological Adaptations

#slide[
  - *Circulatory System*: Higher blood pressure; functionally separate pulmonary and systemic circuits.
  - *Water Conservation*: Excretion of nitrogenous waste as *uric acid* to conserve water.
  - *Nervous System*: Enlarged cerebrum; advanced connections to sensory systems.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-5").path),
  )
]

= Characteristics and Natural History of Reptilian Orders

== Order Testudines (Chelonia): Turtles

#slide[
  - *Shell Structure*: Unique among vertebrates; dorsal *carapace* (背甲) and ventral *plastron* (腹甲).
  - Outer layer of keratin and inner layer of bone (fused ribs/vertebrae).
  - *Limbs*: Uniquely located inside the ribs.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-6").path),
  )
]

== Turtle Feeding and Respiration

#slide[
  - *Feeding*: Lack teeth; jaws covered by tough, keratinized plates forming a beak.
  - *Respiration*: Rigid shell prevents chest expansion; use abdominal/pectoral muscles to breathe.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-7").path),
  )
]

== Turtle Reproduction

#slide[
  - All turtles are oviparous with internal fertilization.
  - Males may have a concave plastron to facilitate mounting.
  - *Senses*: Poor hearing; good smell and color vision.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-8").path),
  )
]

== Temperature-Dependent Sex Determination

#slide[
  - In many turtles, nest temperature determines sex.
  - Typically, low temperatures produce males, and high temperatures produce females.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-9").path),
  )
]

== Sea Turtles

#slide[
  - Large, marine forms with paddle-like limbs.
  - Return to land only to lay eggs.
  - Found in all tropical oceans.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-10").path),
  )
]

== Predation Strategies

#slide[
  - Some turtles, like the Alligator Snapping Turtle, use lures to attract prey.
  - A wormlike protrusion from the tongue lures fish into powerful jaws.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-11").path),
  )
]

== Order Squamata: Lizards and Snakes

#slide[
  - 95% of living nonavian reptiles.
  - *Kinetic skull* (可动颅骨): Movable joints (quadrate) allow snout tilting and seizing/manipulating prey.
  - *Viviparity* (胎生): Evolved ~100 times; associated with cool climates.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-12").path),
  )
]

== Suborder Sauria: Lizards

#slide[
  - Extremely diverse group: geckos, iguanids, skinks, monitors, chameleons.
  - *Senses*: Most have movable eyelids and external ear opening.
  - *Water Conservation*: Excrete semisolid urine (*uric acid*, 尿酸).
]

== Geckos

#slide[
  - Small, agile, nocturnal lizards.
  - Possess adhesive toe pads for climbing.
  - Known for vocalizations (e.g., Tokay gecko).
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-13").path),
  )
]

== Iguanids

#slide[
  - Diverse group including the Marine Iguana.
  - Marine Iguanas feed on algae underwater and have salt glands.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-14").path),
  )
]

== Chameleons

#slide[
  - Arboreal specialists.
  - Features: *Zygodactylous feet* (对趾足), independent eye movement, projectile tongues.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-15").path),
  )
]

== Legless Lizards

#slide[
  - Some lizards, like glass lizards, have lost limbs.
  - Distinguishable from snakes by movable eyelids and external ears.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-16").path),
  )
]

== Venomous Lizards

#slide[
  - Gila monster and Mexican beaded lizard are the only venomous lizards.
  - Venom is chewed into the wound from glands in the lower jaw.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-17").path),
  )
]

== Amphisbaenians ("Worm Lizards")

#slide[
  - Highly specialized for burrowing (*fossorial*, 穴居的).
  - Elongate, cylindrical bodies; reduced/absent limbs; solid skulls for digging.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-18").path),
  )
]

== Suborder Serpentes: Snakes

#slide[
  - Limbless; lack pectoral/pelvic girdles (vestiges in pythons/boas).
  - Highly kinetic skull; mandibles joined only by muscle/skin.
  - Allows swallowing of large prey.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-19").path),
  )
]

== Arboreal Adaptations

#slide[
  - Some snakes have slender bodies for moving through trees.
  - Example: Parrot snake (*Leptophis ahaetulla*).
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-20").path),
  )
]

== Sensory Systems in Snakes

#slide[
  - *Vision*: Transparent *spectacle* (眼罩/透明眼睑) (no eyelids).
  - *Hearing*: No external ears; detect ground vibrations.
  - *Chemoreception*: *Jacobson's organs* (犁鼻器) used with forked tongue.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-21").path),
  )
]

== Snake Locomotion

#slide[
  - *Lateral undulation*: S-shaped path (most common).
  - *Concertina*: Narrow passages.
  - *Rectilinear*: Straight line (heavy snakes).
  - *Side-winding*: Loose sand.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-22").path),
  )
]

== Predation: Constriction

#slide[
  - Suffocating prey by tightening coils.
  - Used by boas, pythons, and some colubrids.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-23").path),
  )
]

== Predation: Venom (Elapids)

#slide[
  - *Elapids*: Permanently erect fangs.
  - Includes cobras, mambas, coral snakes.
  - Venom delivered via fangs.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-24").path),
  )
]

== Predation: Venom (Vipers)

#slide[
  - *Vipers*: Movable tubular fangs that fold back.
  - *Pit Vipers*: Possess heat-sensitive *pit organs* (颊窝) for detecting warm-blooded prey.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-25").path),
  )
]

== Venom Apparatus

#slide[
  - Venom gland is a modified salivary gland.
  - Connected by a duct to the hollow fang.
  - Venom types: *Neurotoxic* (nervous system) and *Hemorrhagin* (blood/tissue).
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-26").path),
  )
]

== Order Sphenodonta: Tuataras

#slide[
  - Sole survivors of sphenodontid lineage (New Zealand).
  - *Characteristics*: Diapsid skull with two complete arches.
  - Well-developed median *parietal eye* (顶眼) (light sensitive).
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-27").path),
  )
]

== Order Crocodilia: Crocodiles and Alligators

#slide[
  - Archosaur lineage (surviving with birds).
  - *Characteristics*: Elongate skull; *thecodont* dentition (槽生齿); *secondary palate* (次生腭); 4-chambered heart.
  - *Behavior*: Parental care; vocalizations.
][
  #figure(
    image(images.at("figure-26-28").path),
  )
]
